body.p:
Let us examine how to determine the empirical formula from the mass of each 
      element in a sample. A sample is composed of 
      42.2gram of carbon
      and 112.0gram of 
      oxygen. Dividing the mass of each element by its molar mass will give us the 
      number of mole of each element in the sample:
      \ch{C}: \frac{42.2gram}
        {12gram per mole}
        = 3.517mole,\quad 
        \ch{O}: \frac{112.0gram}
        {16gram per mole}
        = 7mole.

This gives us a ratio of carbon to oxygen of $3.517:7$. However,
      an empirical formula represents the simplest whole number ratio. We can divide
      the number of mole of each element by the smallest number of mole to try to
      convert the ratio to whole numbers:
      \ch{C}: \frac{3.517mole}
        {3.517mole}
       = 1,\quad 
       \ch{O}: \frac{7mole}
        {3.517mole}
       = 1.990 \approx 2.

answer.p:
To determine the empirical formula, we begin by dividing the total mass of
              each element by its molar mass:
              \ch{Hg}: \frac{40.2gram}{201gram per mole}
                = 0.2mole,\quad 
                \ch{O}:\frac{3.2gram}{16gram per mole}
                =0.2mole.

body.p:
There will be occasions when solving for the empirical formula where a whole number 
      ratio is not produced when dividing by the smallest number of mole.
      Let us consider the following mathematical steps:
      \text{@Step } 1 &: \ch{C}: 
        \frac{40.92gram}
        {12gram per mole} 
        = 3.41mole \quad
        \ch{H}: \frac{4.58gram}
        {1gram per mole} 
        = 4.58mole	\quad
        \ch{O}: \frac{54.50gram}
        {16gram per mole} 
        = 3.41mole\\
        \text{@Step } 2&: \ch{C}: 
        \frac{3.41mole}
        {3.41mole} = 1	\qquad \qquad 
        \ch{H}: \frac{4.58mole}
        {3.41mole} = 1.34 \qquad 	
        \ch{O}: \frac{3.41mole}
        {3.41mole} = 1

answer.p:
Next, we can convert the mass of each element into mole by dividing
          by the molar mass:
          \ch{V}: \frac{68gram}
            {51gram per mole}
            = 1.333mole,	\quad
            \ch{O}: \frac{32gram}
            {16gram per mole} 
            = 2mole.

Now, we can determine the ratio by dividing the number of 
          mole of each
          element by the smallest number of 
          mole:

          \ch{V}: \frac{1.333mole}
            {1.333mole}
            = 1,	\quad
            \ch{O}: \frac{2mole}
            {1.333mole} 
            = 1.5.

body.p:
We can follow these steps to determine the molecular formula from the molar mass 
      and empirical formula. First, we will calculate the molar mass of the empirical 
      formula:
      \begin{align*}\text{@molarmassofempiricalformula} 
        &= \left(5 \times \text{ @molarmassofcarbon} \right) 
        + \left(4 \times \text{ @molarmassofhydrogen} \right)\\
        \text{@molarmassofempiricalformula} 
        &= \left(5 \times 12gram per mole \right) 
        + \left(4 \times 1gram per mole \right) 
        = 64gram per mole.\end{align*}

Then, we will divide the molar mass of the molecule by the molar mass of the empirical 
      formula. The answer should be a whole number or very close to a whole number:
      \begin{align*}\frac{\text{@molarmassofnaphthalene}}
        {\text{@molarmassofnaphthalenesempiricalformula}} 
        = \frac{128gram per mole}
        {64gram per mole} = 2.\end{align*}

answer.p:
Next, we will divide the molar mass of the compound by the molar mass of the 
          empirical formula to produce an integer:
          \begin{align*}\frac{\text{@molarmassofcompound}}{\text{@molarmassofcompoundsempiricalformula}}
            = \frac{339gram per mole}
            {113gram per mole} = 3.\end{align*}

Next, we will convert the mass of each element into mole by dividing by the molar
          mass:
          \ch{C}: \frac{26.7gram}
            {12gram per mole} 
            = 2.225mole, \quad 
            \ch{O}: \frac{71.1gram}
            {16gram per mole} 
            = 4.444mole, \quad 
            \ch{H}: \frac{2.2gram}
            {1gram per mole} 
            = 2.2mole.

This tells us that the molar ratio of carbon to hydrogen to oxygen is 
          $2.225:4.444:2.2$. We can divide the number of 
          mole of
          each element by the smallest number of 
          mole to 
          try to convert the ratio to whole numbers:
          \ch{C}: \frac{2.225mole}
            {2.2mole} 
            = 1.011 \approx 1, \quad 
            \ch{O}: \frac{4.444mole}
            {2.2mole} 
            = 2.02 \approx 2, \quad 
            \ch{H}: \frac{2.2mole}
            {2.2mole} 
            = 1.

Then, we divide the molar mass of oxalic acid by the molar mass of the empirical formula:
          \begin{align*}\frac{\text{@molarmassofoxalicacid}}
            {\text{@molarmassofoxalicacidsempiricalformula}} 
            = \frac{90gram per mole}
            {30gram per mole} = 3.\end{align*}
